I could not have asked for a more fitting final moment in my conducting career. I was so proud of these students, and the singular composition which could have provided it was your "Inchon", so...thank you. I love your tone poems, and this is the best of all. 9/end

She played the solo beautifully, and looked stunning. She played from memory and I honestly had a tear on my cheek when she was finishing. The effect of the incoming landing was very effective and the band was dialed in perfectly. 8/

When she walked out, there was a collective gasp, and then you could have heard a pin drop. The percussionists with the bass heads had taken up there positions. The auditorium was perfect for this effect as it had a very steep angle to the audience seating and a balcony. 7/

I told her if she didn't wear it for the concert, I'd never let her in my rehearsal room again. In the day of the concert, I introduced the piece with a background on the Korean conflict, the significance of helicopters during the time, and the Inchon landing. 6/

She had brought with her an elaborate hanbok, the traditional ceremonial clothing of Korea, and wanted to know if I would allow her to wear it while performing. She opened up a simple canvas garment bag with leather and bone toggle fasteners, and showed me a gorgeous dress. 5/

She wasn't the most talented of the flute players in the section, but all of the band members were required to take private lessons, so I knew she'd have it down pat by May, and I was right. The week before the concert, she said she wanted to ask me something. 4/

In fact, it wasn't until after marching season that it dawned on me the significance of her being a flutist. I had always allowed for any student to challenge for that type of feature solo, but I knew IMMEDIATELY this solo would not be challenged. 3/

As fate would have it, there was a flute player in my band that year who was an exchange student from Korea.  I had no idea we would be having an exchange student that year when I chose the piece after hearing it at a music educators conference. 2/

@rwsmithcomposer I don't know if you'll ever see this, but I felt the need to share. As a former high school music director, now some 18 years removed from the profession, my greatest conducting memory was the performance of "Inchon" at the final concert I conducted. 1/
